                <div class="faq-expanded__list">
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-1">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Which ROC handles object clause change in Mumbai?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>ROC Mumbai at Everest House, 100 Marine Lines, Mumbai 400020. Form MGT-14 and E-MOA (INC-33) filed electronically on MCA V3 portal. ROC processes filing and updates MCA Master Data with amended objects and NIC codes. Patron's office at Marine Lines is adjacent to ROC Everest House.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-2">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the object clause of a company?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Clause III of the MOA defined under Section 4(1)(c). Specifies the business activities the company is legally permitted to conduct. Divided into primary objects (purposes of incorporation) and ancillary matters (activities necessary to further those objects). Activities outside stated objects are ultra vires and void. Patron reviews and drafts object clauses for Mumbai companies.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-3">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What resolution is required for object clause change?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Special Resolution with 75% majority at EGM or postal ballot under Section 13(1). Stricter than ordinary resolution because the object clause is a fundamental MOA provision. EGM requires 21 clear days' notice with explanatory statement detailing the proposed amendment. Patron drafts the Special Resolution and conducts the EGM.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-4">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What is the Doctrine of Ultra Vires?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>Ultra vires means 'beyond the powers'. If a company conducts business activities not listed in its object clause, those activities are legally void. Contracts for ultra vires activities cannot be enforced. Directors authorising them may be personally liable. Patron recommends immediate amendment to regularise operations and eliminate this risk.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-5">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">How long does the process take?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>10-20 working days for private limited companies: drafting (Day 1-3), board meeting (Day 3-5), EGM (Day 7-26), filing MGT-14 and E-MOA (within 30 days), ROC processing (3-7 days). With 95% shorter notice consent, can complete in 10-12 days. Public companies require additional time for newspaper publication.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-6">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Can the object clause be changed retroactively?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. The amendment is prospective &ndash; applies only to future activities from the date of ROC registration. Past activities outside original objects remain ultra vires. However, amending regularises ongoing and future operations. Patron advises proactive amendment before conducting new activities, not after.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-7">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">Is INC-24 required for object clause change?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>No. INC-24 is specifically for company name change (Clause I). Object clause change (Clause III) requires only Form MGT-14 (resolution filing) and E-MOA (INC-33). This is a common confusion. For Mumbai companies changing multiple MOA clauses simultaneously, Patron coordinates all filings together for efficiency.</p></div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="faq-expanded__item" id="faq-8">
                        <h3 class="faq-expanded__q">What are NIC codes and why do they matter?</h3>
                        <div class="faq-expanded__a"><p>NIC (National Industrial Classification) 2008 codes classify business activities into standardised categories. When filing E-MOA (INC-33), the company must select NIC codes corresponding to its objects. These appear on MCA Master Data and are used for statistical classification, GST alignment, and regulatory mapping. Incorrect codes create downstream compliance issues.</p></div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>


